---
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  { q: 'How do I convert text to voice online free?', a: 'Use TextWonder\'s Text to Speech tool — paste your text, choose a voice and speed, and click Speak. It uses your browser\'s built-in speech synthesis. No signup or software required.' },
  { q: 'What is the best free text to voice converter online?', a: 'TextWonder\'s Text to Speech tool is free, browser-based, and uses the Web Speech API to access high-quality voices built into your operating system. No account, no limits.' },
  { q: 'How do I convert text to audio and download it as an MP3?', a: 'Browser-based Text to Speech tools play audio directly but cannot export MP3 files due to browser security restrictions. To save as audio, use your device\'s screen recording or a desktop app like Balabolka (Windows) or Say (Mac command line).' },
  { q: 'What is the difference between text to voice and text to speech?', a: '"Text to voice", "text to speech", and "text to audio" all mean the same thing: converting written text into spoken audio output using a speech synthesis engine.' },
  { q: 'Can I convert text to voice in a different language?', a: 'Yes. The Text to Speech tool lists all voices installed on your device, which typically include multiple languages. Select a voice in your target language from the dropdown before clicking Speak.' },
  { q: 'How do I convert text to audio online for free without any software?', a: 'Open TextWonder\'s Text to Speech tool in your browser. Paste your text, select a voice, and click Speak. Everything runs in the browser using the Web Speech API — no software installation needed.' },
];
---

<BlogLayout
  title="How to Convert Text to Voice Online Free — Text to Audio Converter"
  description="Convert text to voice online for free. Use the free Text to Speech tool — paste any text, choose a voice and speed, and listen instantly. No signup, no software needed."
  canonical="/blog/how-to-convert-text-to-voice"
  date="2026-06-23"
  readTime="4 min read"
  category="Text Utilities"
  faqs={faqs}
>

<p>
  Converting text to voice (also called text to speech or text to audio) lets you listen to any written content — articles, notes, emails, or scripts — hands-free. TextWonder's free tool uses your browser's built-in speech synthesis to speak any text instantly, with no signup or software required.
</p>

<a href="/devwonder/text-to-speech" class="tool-cta">
  <div class="cta-label">Free Tool — No Signup</div>
  <div class="cta-title">Text to Speech Converter →</div>
  <div class="cta-desc">Paste any text and hear it spoken aloud. Choose from multiple voices, adjust speed (0.5×–2×) and pitch. Free, browser-based, works offline.</div>
</a>

<h2>How to Convert Text to Voice Online</h2>

<ol>
  <li>Open <a href="/devwonder/text-to-speech">TextWonder's Text to Speech tool</a>.</li>
  <li>Paste or type your text into the input area.</li>
  <li>Choose a voice from the dropdown — voices vary by your device and browser (Windows, Mac, and mobile each have different built-in voices).</li>
  <li>Adjust the <strong>speed</strong> (0.5× to 2×) and <strong>pitch</strong> if needed.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Speak</strong>. The text is read aloud through your speakers or headphones.</li>
  <li>Use <strong>Pause</strong>, <strong>Resume</strong>, or <strong>Stop</strong> to control playback.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Convert Text to Audio Online Free — Use Cases</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Proofreading:</strong> Listen to your writing to catch errors your eyes miss.</li>
  <li><strong>Accessibility:</strong> Convert articles or documents to audio for people with visual impairments or reading difficulties.</li>
  <li><strong>Language learning:</strong> Hear correct pronunciation of words or sentences in another language.</li>
  <li><strong>Multitasking:</strong> Have emails, notes, or web content read aloud while you do other things.</li>
  <li><strong>Presentations:</strong> Preview how a script sounds before recording a voiceover.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Get More Voices</h2>

<p>
  The available voices depend on your operating system and browser:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Go to <strong>Settings → Time &amp; Language → Speech</strong> → click <strong>Add voices</strong> to install more languages and voice packs.</li>
  <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Go to <strong>System Settings → Accessibility → Spoken Content</strong> → click the System Voice dropdown → <strong>Manage Voices</strong> to download additional voices.</li>
  <li><strong>Chrome:</strong> Chrome on Windows adds Google-powered voices (like "Google US English") which tend to sound more natural than Windows built-in voices.</li>
</ul>

<h2>How to Save Text to Audio as an MP3</h2>

<p>
  Browser-based Text to Speech uses the <strong>Web Speech API</strong>, which plays audio directly but cannot export it as a downloadable audio file. To save the speech as an audio file:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Windows:</strong> Use the built-in screen recorder (Win+G) to record system audio while the tool speaks. Then extract the audio from the video.</li>
  <li><strong>Mac:</strong> Use QuickTime Player → New Audio Recording (set input to system audio) while the tool is speaking.</li>
  <li><strong>Dedicated tools for MP3 export:</strong> Balabolka (Windows, free), Google Text-to-Speech in Google Translate (copy text → click the speaker icon → right-click the audio player → Save audio as), or ElevenLabs for high-quality AI voices.</li>
</ul>

<div class="faq-section">
<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
{faqs.map(f => (
  <details class="bg-[var(--bg-surface)] border border-slate-800 rounded-xl group mb-2">
